6.Qualification as standard amendment
The competent authority considers this amendment to the 'Uclés' PDO product specification to be a standard
amendment; it cannot be regarded as a Union amendment since it does not correspond to any of the situations
referred to in Article 24(3) of Regulation (EU) 2024/1143 on geographical indications. Specifically, it does not:
include a change in the name or in the use of the name, or in the category of product or products designated by the
geographical indication; risk voiding the link with the geographical area; entail further restrictions on the marketing
of the product.
7.Description of the approved standard amendment(s)
Title
CORRECTION TO THE TERMINOLOGY USED FOR THE SUGARS

( ) Commission Delegated Regulation (EU) 2025/27 of 30 October 2024 supplementing Regulation (EU) 2024/1143 of the European Parliament and of the Council with rules concerning the registration and the protection of geographical indications, traditional specialities guaranteed and optional quality terms and repealing Delegated Regulation (EU) No 664/2014 (OJ L, 2025/27, 15.1.2025, ELI: http://data.europa.eu/eli/reg_del/2025/27/oj).

The analytical parameter 'residual sugar' has been renamed 'total sugars'. These changes have been made in the section on the analytical characteristics of all the final products. It has also been specified that the limit is expressed in terms of 'fructose and glucose', and for quality sparkling wines in terms of 'fructose, glucose and sucrose'.
Points 2.1 and 2.2 of the product specification have been amended but the single document is not affected.
The amendment affects the single document.
CORRECTION TO THE REFERENCE TO A PRODUCT CATEGORY

The beginning of point 2 of the product specification (Description of the wines) refers to category 5 in Part II of Annex VII to Regulation (EU) No 1308/2013 of 17 December 2013. In the rest of the text, however, instead of referring to them as 'quality sparkling wines', which is category 5, the wines were mistakenly listed as 'sparkling wines', which is category 4. This error has been corrected.
Points 2 and 3 of the product specification and point 6 of the single document have been amended.
The amendment affects the single document.
CHANGES TO THE LIMITS FOR ANALYTICAL CHARACTERISTICS
The maximum actual alcoholic strength limit for red wines, young white wines and quality sparkling wines has been removed.
The minimum total acidity of the red wines has been reduced from 4,5 g/l to 4 g/l.
Point 2.1 of the product specification and point 6 of the single document have been amended.
The amendment affects the single document.
Various aspects of the organoleptic description of the wines have been amended.
Point 2.3 of the product specification and point 6 of the single document have been amended.
The amendment affects the single document.
For 'Crianza' red wines, the words 'two calendar years' have been replaced by the words '24 months' and the requirement regarding time spent in the bottle has been removed.
For 'Reserva' red wines, the words 'counted from the date of harvest' have been deleted in reference to the point from which the 36 months of ageing are counted.
Points 3.1.2 and 3.1.3 of the product specification have been amended but the single document is not affected.
The amendment affects the single document.
The parcels located in polygons 12, 17, 18, 19, 72 and 73 in the municipality of Corral de Almaguer have been added.
Point 4 of the product specification and point 9 of the single document have been amended.
The amendment affects the single document.
Addition of new vine varieties planted on the parcels located in the new polygons that have been proposed for inclusion in the product specification. The new varieties added are:

• Red: Cabernet Franc, Mazuela (Cariñena), Malbec, Petit Verdot, Tinto Velasco, Graciano and Touriga Nacional.
  • White: Viognier and Albariño.
Point 6 of the product specification and point 8 of the single document have been amended.
The amendment affects the single document.
UPDATED REGULATORY REFERENCES AND DETAILS OF THE COMPETENT AUTHORITY AND DELEGATED BODIES
Reference to the repealed Regulations has been replaced by a reference to the Regulations currently in force, which have replaced them.
The references to the competent authority and delegated control bodies have also been updated.
Points 8 and 9 of the product specification have been amended but the single document is not affected.
The amendment affects the single document.

7.1. Specific oenological practices used to make the wine or wines, relevant restrictions on making them

For young red wines, the must is macerated with the skins for at least four days. If they undergo a short period of ageing, this must not be less than two months spent in barrels, which must be made of oak and have a maximum capacity of 600 litres. For 'Crianza' and 'Reserva' wines, the must is macerated with the skins for at least seven days. For dry white wines, the grape bunches are crushed and the stems and the skins are removed. The grapes are fermented for the length of time needed to fully convert the sugars at a temperature no higher than 22 °C. Maceration on the skins, if carried out, may last no more than six days.

Vineyards with red varieties less than six years old cannot produce wines with the Uclés designation of origin. However, white wines with the Uclés designation of origin may be produced from the vine's first year of production.

9. Concise definition of the demarcated geographical area
It includes parcels located in the following municipalities in the provinces of Cuenca and Toledo:

• Cuenca: Acebrón (El), Alcázar del Rey, Almendros, Belinchón, Carrascosa del Campo, Fuente de Pedro Naharro, Horcajo de Santiago, Huelves, Huete, Langa, Loranca del Campo, Paredes, Pozorrubio, Rozalén del Monte, Saelices, Tarancón, Torrubia del Campo, Tribaldos, Uclés, Valparaíso de Arriba, Valparaíso de Abajo, Vellisca, Villamayor de Santiago, Villarrubio and Zarza de Tajo.
  • Toledo: Cabezamesada: polygons 501 to 505, 507 and 508; Corral de Almáguer: polygons 12, 17 to 25, 72 and 73 and Santa Cruz de la Zarza.

The western half is situated at an elevation of between 500 m and 800 m and the eastern half between 600 m and 1 200 m. The soil is characterised by significant levels of potassium, which provides balance and allows the grapes to ripen well. The soils have a finer texture and tend towards being calcareous, ranging from clay-loam to sandy loam; they are deep soils. The elevation and the potassium-rich soils, combined with the predominance of free-standing gobelet forms and the low planting density, result in grapes with balanced acidity, which produce very balanced wines, and with a low pH, which increases the acidity of the wines, making them well suited to a longer life in the bottle.
